Of intent and content¶

Intent Data?¶

Data that is collected about business web users’ observed behavior - specifically web content consumption - that provides insights into their interests and from this indicate potential intent to take an action.

Bombora does ABC to deliver XYZ

Hypotheses¶

(Bomborian interpretation of Intent)¶

  • H1: User intent is positively correlated with user interest
  • H2: User consumption of (web) content provides an observable and quantifiable action to measure interactions and engagement with topics.
  • H3: Sampling such interactions at scale allows user interest to be inferred across many dimensions (e.g., time, geo, firmographic, demographic).

Intent can be inferred by sampling user-content interactions at scale¶

(Web) Content¶

Web Content: Wikipedia:

is the textual, visual, or aural content that is encountered as part of the user experience on websites. It may include—among other things—text, images, sounds, videos, and animations.

  • a web content concepts of interest can be understood through only text content.
  • $\therefore$ user and text-content interactions are the kernel of interest

How to quantify?¶

Answer: Machine Learning!¶

Reality: Start Somewhere¶

Conceptualize a user + content interaction event to be a user's engagement with topics event.

During interaction, capture:

  1. Topics
  2. Engagement

DS Modeling Endeavor 1: Engagement¶

Not all interactions are the same. Capture that.

(Tony Haile—Chartbeat)

Engagement model¶

ranks a user's engagement with content (low, medium, high).

based on clustering model that considers normalized metrics:

  • dwell time
  • scroll depth
  • scroll velocity
  • device types

We refer to this task as engagement weighting, and is used as a feature in topic interest model.

DS Modeling endeavor 2: Text to Topics¶

text to topics¶

  • consider focused, topic-centric view of the content-universe.

  • transform text-content to an array of topic-concepts (and weights)

this task is known as topic classification

Going Deep in NLP¶

Why DL?¶

  • State-of-the-art performance in supervised learning tasks
  • No feature engineering

In training comparisons, outperforms baseline model 20%*.¶

Topic Classification Service (Tessie)¶

  • Predicts topics from content, extracted from raw file.

Model¶

  • based on open source implementation of NLP on DL (from a big four company)
  • custom corpus of topic-content data (topic taxonomy)
  • leverages wiki corpus word embeddings
  • model selection via Bayesian optimization

Production System¶

  • Runs on scalable processing nodes (Google App Engine)
  • Cost 10% of previous service

Topic Taxonomy¶

in Bombora lexicon:

a classification framework that organizes verbal content into individually-addressable items, which are called topics. Content consumption across the Bombora co-op is captured, and topics are assigned to the content and weighted for relevancy.

Now what?¶

Observe lots of interactions!¶

HOW?¶

Data co-op: observe, at scale¶

the Bombora data co-op (DCO) is our B2B intent radio telescope network, finding interest-heavy topic-stars, scattered across domain galaxies in the internet cosmos.

  • a tag-powered publisher acts as telescope, observing an (incredibly) small slice of content-interactions across the internet night sky
  • collectively, contribute their content-interaction observations to a global pool
  • continuous, real-time stream of observations

Collects one billion observations/day (no more MongoDB)!¶

Historical Daily Event Counts¶

DS Modeling Endeavor 3: Topic Interest¶

Detect when interest in a topic is significantly (positive) from a particular domain

  • Observe domain behaviors (normalized features) over time to establish profile / baseline
  • compare current behavior with past baseline

We refer to this task as anomaly detection.

Topic Interest Score Model (Surge)¶

computes topic interest scores (a measure of topic interest across space, time, and company)

  • leverages aggregated statistics of Bombora event datasets, yielding daily observations across different dimensions.
  • combined and normalized to produce a desired feature setfor the model:
    • event counts
    • user counts
    • topic score weightings
    • engagement weightings)
  • considers daily activity of the feature set of a 3-week current interval (i.e., 21 observations across all features), and compares it against a distribution of daily activity from a 12-week baseline (i.e., 84 observations).

Closing the circle in interest inferring intent¶

Two methods:

  • Look Forward: campaign case studies (aka bake offs)

Topic Interest Historical Analysis (TIHA)¶

allows for understanding Bombora Topic Surge data product potential application across a variety of customer use cases. This is performed by providing a comparison of surge behavior domain and topic subset of interest, during an known historical sales cycle.
